In [[linguistic morphology]], '''fossilization''' refers to two close notions. One is preserving of ancient linguistic features which have lost their grammatical functions in [[language]]. Another is loss of [[Productivity (linguistics)|productivity]] of a grammatical paradigm (''e.g.'' of an [[affix]]), which still remains in use in some words.<ref>''The Dictionary of Historical and Comparative Linguistics'', by Robert Lawrence Trask, Another definition of fossilization: fossilization is a process in which incorrect linguistic features become a permanent part a person speaks and writes in a language. [https://books.google.com/books?id=EHeGzQ8wuLQC&pg=PA126&lpg=PA126&dq=%22fossilized+form%22+linguistics&source=web&ots=ViAhkdCfBP&sig=28qoQp08oJBheqA2iYc5XspXoJE&hl=en&sa=X&oi=book_result&resnum=1&ct=result#PPA125,M1 p. 125]</ref>
Examples of fossilization include [[Bound morpheme|fossilized morpheme]]s and [[fossil word]]s.
