'''Mario Pino Quivira''' is a [[Chile]]an [[geologist]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://noticias.universia.cl/vida-universitaria/noticia/2007/10/22/317160/universidad-austral-inicia-excavaciones-importante-estudio-paleontologico.html|title=UNIVERSIDAD-AUSTRAL-INICIA-EXCAVACIONES-IMPORTANTE-ESTUDIO-PALEONTOLOGICO|date=22 October 2007|work=Universia|language=Portuguese|accessdate=15 July 2011}}</ref> specialized in [[geoarchaeology]] and [[sedimentology]] that has been involved in several studies of early human settlements in [[Southern Chile]]. After [[Tom Dillehay]]'s excavation of [[Monte Verde]] near [[Puerto Montt]], where human remains estimated to be about 12,800 years old have been found, challenging the [[Clovis theory]] of the [[Models of migration to the New World|first human arrival in the Americas]],<ref>{{cite news|title = Chilean Field Yields New Clues to Peopling of Americas|date = 25 August 1998|url = https://www.nytimes.com/1998/08/25/science/chilean-field-yields-new-clues-to-peopling-of-americas.html|last = Wilford|first = John Noble|newspaper = New York Times|accessdate = 26 November 2013}}</ref> Pino controversially claimed the site was 33,000 years old.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.nationalgeographic.com/events/97/monteverde/dallas.html|title = CHILEAN SITE VERIFIED AS EARLIEST HABITATION OF AMERICAS; FINDINGS SHOW MONTE VERDE DATES BACK 12,500 YEARS|accessdate = 26 November 2013|website = National Geographic|deadurl = yes|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20131202232355/http://www.nationalgeographic.com/events/97/monteverde/dallas.html|archivedate = 2 December 2013|df = }}</ref> Other studied sites includes the [[Chan-Chan]] settlement near [[Mehuín]]<ref>{{cite journal|title = Geoarchaeology of the archaic site Chan-Chan 18, coast of Valdivia: environmental discrimination of human occupation and its relation with the middle Holocene marine transgression.|date = 2005|url = http://www.andeangeology.equipu.cl/index.php../revista1/article/view/V32n1-a05|last = Pino|first = Mario|last2 = Navarro|first2 = Rayen X.|journal = [[Andean Geology]]|volume = 32|issue = 1|doi = 10.5027/andgeoV32n1-a05}}</ref> and the [[Pilauco Bajo|Gomphotherium of Osorno]].<ref>{{Cite journal|title = The late Pleistocene Pilauco site, Osorno, south-central Chile|date = 2012|url = http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1040618212003199|last = Pino|journal = [[Quaternary International]]|doi = 10.1016/j.quaint.2012.05.001|volume = 299|pages = 3–12|display-authors=etal|bibcode = 2013QuInt.299....3P}}</ref>

