{{mergeto|Timeline of the gunpowder age|date=January 2018}}
{{see also|Timeline of the gunpowder age}}

This is a timeline of the history of [[gunpowder]] and related topics such as weapons, warfare, and industrial applications in [[Southeast Asia]].

==14th century==
{| class="wikitable" width="100%"
! style="width:6%" | Year || style="width:10%" | Date || Event
|-
|1293
|
|The [[Mongol invasion of Java]] brought firearms and gunpowder to Nusantaran archipelago<ref>Dr. J.L.A. Brandes, T.B.G., LII (1910)</ref>
|-
|1350
|
|Empire of [[Majapahit]] reached its full extent. Majapahit military commander Mpu Nala used [[Cetbang]] for Majapahit conquests.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://penggiatbudayakediri.blogspot.co.id/2014/10/prasasti-sekar.html|title=Sekar Inscriptions|last=|first=|date=|website=Kediri Culture|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-08-06}}</ref>
|-
| 1352 || || Cannons are mentioned to have been used by the [[Ayutthaya Kingdom]] in their invasion of the [[Khmer Empire]]{{sfn|Purton|2010|p=201}}
|-
| 1360 || || [[Gunpowder]] barrels aboard a [[Khmer Empire|Khmer]] ship explode.{{sfn|Purton|2010|p=201}}
|-
| 1388 || || ''[[Ming–Mong Mao War (1386–1388)|Ming–Mong Mao War]]'': [[Volley fire]] is implemented with [[cannon]]s by the [[Ming dynasty|Ming]] artillery corps in the anti-insurrection war waged against the [[Mong Mao]].{{sfn|Andrade|2016|p=157}}
|-
| 1390 || || [[Trần dynasty]] soldiers kill the king of [[Champa]], Che Bong Nga, using [[hand cannon]]s.{{sfn|Tran|2006|p=75}}
|}

==15th century==
{| class="wikitable" width="100%"
! style="width:6%" | Year || style="width:10%" | Date || Event
|-
| 1471 || || ''[[Cham–Annamese War]]'': [[Lê dynasty]] troops use cannons to blast a breach in [[Vijaya (Champa)|Vijaya]]'s fortifications prior to capturing the city{{sfn|Purton|2010|p=202}}
|}

==16th century==
{| class="wikitable" width="100%"
! style="width:6%" | Year || style="width:10%" | Date || Event
